<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">the vessels generally make coming from Camanitiquia: and near the entrance of the bay there are two Small Islands round which there is good anchorage which enables a vessel to hold what she has already made in case of a Northeasterly gale.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Pique of Nipagon which projects considerably into the lake and is exactly opposite to Keegwajnan forms a kind of strait and is the narrowest part of the main body of the Lake not being more than thirty or forty leagues over.  From Grand Island to Michipiquaton on the North shore it is at least eighty leagues broad and about thirty leagues to the South West of Keegwajnan; from the Porcupine Mountain of which I shall speak shortly to the bottom of the great black bay which approaches the Hudson's Bay Territories on the opposite side, the distance cannot be less than 120 or 130 leagues.  The greatest length of Lake Superior is reckoned from Metal Toad Cape to what the French call Fond du Lac, or the bottom of the Lake, which I am certain is not less than 150 leagues.</p>

